We just purchased some of the following cable…

https://www.amazon.com/dp/B09C2HRQ7L?ref=ppx_yo2_dt_b_product_details&th=1

We are having some issues getting the cable in the Wago Connectors on the PDH as well as the lugs for the main breaker.

Teams that use large 6AWG or 4 AWG cables, are you also using that on the main battery connector, and if so, have you found any lugs that work well with larger cable, have you had any success using it with the PDH either? Finally, do you have any recommendations for the APP lugs?

Edit: These are the lugs we are using for our main breaker. They almost work, but all the fine strands are impossible to get in there. We typically up our silicone wire connector size (we use the 45 APP for all of our silicone 12 gauge connections even though the 30 should work).

andymark.com

6 Gauge Compression Lug Connector 1/4 Stud Hole BURNDY #: YAZV6CTC14FX

06 gauge Compression Lug

4awg ought to be used with the SB120 APP connector. The KoP stuff is an SB50.

We did not notice any issues installing stripped 4awg in the Rev PDH with this wire: Battery Wire, 600V AC/DC, with EPDM Outer Insulation, 4 Wire Gauge | McMaster-Carr

You can fit 4awg into SB50 connectors, you just need to flare them out some. IMO this is worth it so that your batteries remain SB50 so other teams/rookies/etc can continue to borrow batteries from you and such.

Stripped 4awg wire should fit into the input port on the PDH (that size WAGO port is rated for 4awg).

you just need to flare them out some.

The reason your 6 AWG wire does not fit the lugs meant for 6AWG wire is because not all wire of some nominal AWG size are made the same way so there is a range of conductor sizes.

The wire stranding chart from Calmont lists 17 different stranding variations for 6 AWG wire ranging from solid 1 strand with a conductor diameter of 0.162 inches/4.11 mm up to 6517 strands of 44 AWG with a coductor diameter of 0.224 inches/5.68 mm. The largest variant has 1813 strands of 38 AWG has a conductor size of 0.238 inches/6.00 mm which is 46% larger than the smallest.

One of the photos for the wire you are using has a conductor size chart showing it si made from 3200 strands of 0.08 mm (aprox 40 AWG) and the conductor diameter is 5.20 mm.

This link to a product selection search for 6 AWG on the Alpha Wire website shows that the most common form of construction they use is 133 strands of 27 AWG which would have a conductor size of 0.213 inches/5.41 mm.

I spent a week at a previous job making a giant spread sheet showing all the high-strand count cables used in several of our product ranges, their conductor sizes and the hole sizes in all the circuit breakers, contactors and terminal blocks so we could choose new lugs for those components so that the cables would actually fit.
